word_summaries_chapter_106:
  106:1:1:"The first word of verse (106:1) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and verbal noun. The prefixed preposition <i class=\"ab\">lām</i> is usually translated as \"for\". The form IV verbal noun is masculine and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The verbal noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hamza lām fā</i> (<span class=\"at\">أ ل ف</span>). Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  106:1:2:"The second word of verse (106:1) is a plural proper noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>)."
  106:2:1:"The first word of verse (106:2) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A verbal noun and possessive pronoun. The form IV verbal noun is masculine and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The verbal noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hamza lām fā</i> (<span class=\"at\">أ ل ف</span>). The attached possessive pronoun is third person masculine plural."
  106:2:2:"The second word of verse (106:2) is a feminine noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā ḥā lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر ح ل</span>)."
  106:2:3:"The third word of verse (106:2) is a masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">shīn tā wāw</i> (<span class=\"at\">ش ت و</span>)."
  106:2:4:"The fourth word of verse (106:2) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and noun. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The noun is masculine and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ṣād yā fā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ص ي ف</span>)."
  106:3:1:"The first word of verse (106:3) is divided into 4 morphological segments. A conjunction, imperative particle, verb and subject pronoun. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">fa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The prefixed particle <i class=\"ab\">lām</i> is usually translated as \"let\" and is used to form an imperative construction. The imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>) is third person masculine plural and is in the jussive mood (<span class=\"at\">مجزوم</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn bā dāl</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع ب د</span>). The suffix (<span class=\"at\">الواو</span>) is an attached subject pronoun."
  106:3:2:"The second word of verse (106:3) is a masculine noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā bā bā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر ب ب</span>)."
  106:3:3:"The third word of verse (106:3) is a masculine singular demonstrative pronoun."
  106:3:4:"The fourth word of verse (106:3) is a masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">bā yā tā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ب ي ت</span>)."
  106:4:1:"The first word of verse (106:4) is a masculine singular relative pronoun."
  106:4:2:"The second word of verse (106:4) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A verb and object pronoun. The form IV perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is third person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ṭā ʿayn mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ط ع م</span>). The attached object pronoun is third person masculine plural."
  106:4:3:"The third word of verse (106:4) is a preposition."
  106:4:4:"The fourth word of verse (106:4) is an indefinite masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">jīm wāw ʿayn</i> (<span class=\"at\">ج و ع</span>)."
  106:4:5:"The fifth word of verse (106:4) is divided into 3 morphological segments. A conjunction, verb and object pronoun. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The form IV perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is third person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hamza mīm nūn</i> (<span class=\"at\">أ م ن</span>). The attached object pronoun is third person masculine plural."
  106:4:6:"The sixth word of verse (106:4) is a preposition."
  106:4:7:"The seventh word of verse (106:4) is an indefinite masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">khā wāw fā</i> (<span class=\"at\">خ و ف</span>)."